\begin_layout Standard
Modulo is about the remainder.
 E.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $1\mod3=1$
\end_inset

, because 
\begin_inset Formula $1/3=0,rem=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2\mod3=2$
\end_inset

, because 
\begin_inset Formula $2/3=0,$
\end_inset

rem=2.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $5\mod3=2$
\end_inset

, because 
\begin_inset Formula $5/3=1,rem=2$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $0\mod n=0$
\end_inset

.
 Integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mod n$
\end_inset

 therefore means all integers up to 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Typically, the modulo is defined as positive remainder, even for negative
 numbers.
 In this approach, the negative value is shifted by the modvalue until the
 result is positive and the remainder can be calculated.
 E.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $-7\mod5=3$
\end_inset

, because 
\begin_inset Formula $-7+2\cdot5=3$
\end_inset

 and hence the remainder is 3; 
\begin_inset Formula $-1\mod3\rightarrow-1+3=2\rightarrow0,rem\,2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This aligns with the definition of the Euclidean division.
 which always has positive remainder.
 Another example: -17/5=4, remainder=3.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some approaches use negative remainders, then the application is as usual,
 using division with sign, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $-7/5=-1,rem=-2$
\end_inset

.
 The positive definition can also be thought of shifting negative remainders
 by the mod value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that equations such as 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{r}=1\,\mod p$
\end_inset

 are to be read as follows: the remainder of 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{r}/p$
\end_inset

 should be 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mod p$
\end_inset

 is applied to the left side!
\end_layout

